Any additional comments you'd like to in: This cycle included clomid and letrozole for the first five days of stims. Re: day results: We only had one good-looking grade B day 5 blast, which tested PGS abnormal ("chaotic"). We also had 4 slow-growing grade C-"early blasts" on day 6, which the embryologist expected would degenerate by day 7 (based on our prior two cycles where everything degenerated). I begged them to biopsy them anyway, in the hopes that it would give us useful information about the underlying cause of our infertility. We were shocked to learn that one of the C- early blasts was PGS normal. Our RE wants us to attempt a transfer, but the embryologist has cautioned that there is a 50% chance the embryo won't survive being thawed.

- removed all toxins possible
I avoided hair dying, mani/pedis, facials, Botox, fake lashes, no body lotions, etc
- changed all household and beauty products to zero toxins
- installed Reverse Osmosis water system in our house
- only drink from BPA free glass
- No storing and heating food up in plastic
- Cooked with Stainless Steel and Cast Iron
- daily fertility affirmations and meditations
- Chinese Acupuncture 2x week
- walk 4-5 miles daily
- ate organic as much as possible
- nitrate free meats
- no alcohol, gluten, dairy, caffeine
- IF 16:8, Whole 30 / Ketoish diet
- listened to fertility podcasts daily

Any additional comments you'd like to in: IVF for fertility preservation ahead of cancer treatment. I had never tried to conceive before this point so I don't know whether I had any preexisting fertility issues. My AMH was quite low for my age, which the RE said could either just be natural/normal for me, or suppressed due to the previous chemotherapy I'd completed 3 months before. Because my left ovary was hiding during the baseline scan, I was not given an exact AFC but I believe there were 6 or 8 follicles on the right ovary. I also wasn't given an exact number of day 3 embryos, just told "most" were still growing. The cycle cost was reduced through a compassionate program, and they also provided medications at cost for an additional $3500 which was then refunded by the clinic's insurance after cycle completion. We did not do PGT testing, since it wasn't presented as an option to us and after I learned about it the extra cost and risk of damage to the embryos from thawing/refreezing didn't seem worth it.
